Recall that a nonempty topological space $X$ is {\it strongly zero-dimensional}, if it is completely regular and every finite functionally open cover of $X$ has a finite disjoint open refinement~\cite[ñ.~529]{Eng}.

\begin{theorem}
    Let $X$ be a strongly zero-dimensional metrizable space, let $Y$ and $Z$ be topological spaces. Then $(X,Y,Z)$ is a Lebesgue triple.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof} Let $d$ be a metric on $X$, which generates its topology.
